<HEADLINE> Iran Claims 10-Billion-Dollar Compensation from </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 13 (Xinhua) -- An Iranian official today urged
the government to speed up the procedure for claiming 18.3 billion
Deutsche marks (10.6 billion U.S. dollars) from Germany for
damages incurred to a submarine contract and suspension of a
nuclear power plant in southern port city of Bushehr.
</P>
<P>
Hassan Rowhani, First Vice-Speaker of the Parliament, today
also called on the government to fully revise Tehran's relations
with Bonn at the open session of the Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Iran ordered two 1,200-megawatt units from the West German
firm of Kraftwerk Union in mid 1970s. The twin generating units,
named "Iran No. 1" and "Iran No. 2", were sited at Halileh, a
village 12 kilometers southeast of Bushehr.
</P>
<P>
Germany suspended the project during the eight-year Iran-Iraq
war (1980-1988) and refused to complete the project after the
Islamic revolution in 1979, under the pressure from the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Russia has taken over the deal after it signed a
1-billion-dollar contract with Iran in January 1995.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that Iran's claim for compensation
indicates the escalation of the diplomatic battle between Bonn
and Tehran.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have already recalled their ambassadors and
expelled four diplomats from each other shortly after the
Thursday's verdict of the Berlin court charging top Iranian
leaders with ordering the killing of four Kurdish opposition
leaders in a Berlin restaurant in 1992.
</P>
<P>
However, Iran's official news agency IRNA did not specify
whether the Iranian government will downgrade or sever the
diplomatic ties.
</P>
<P>
Some Iranian parliament members have already urged the
government to break up the diplomatic and economic ties with
Bonn in a protest against the court verdict.
</P>
<P>
Rowhani, who is also secretary of the Supreme National
Security Council, requested the judiciary to speed up legal
action against the German firms, which supplied Iraq with
long-range missiles and chemical arms during the Iran-Iraq war.
</P>
<P>
He said that the parliament would follow reassessment of
relations between Iran and Bonn through its special commission on
foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
The official also criticized the European Union for recalling
their ambassadors, threatening that "Iran will reciprocate."
</P>
<P>
He said the government's decision to suspend Iranian
contracts with New Zealand as well as a visit to Tehran by an
Australian delegation was "a timely act."
</P>
<P>
Rowhani warned that Iran would take into consideration the
moves of the EU members and would adopt necessary decisions to
deal with them.
</P>
<P>
"we should remind the European states that gone is
the time for imposing unilateral views and expectations on
others in international relations and that the European states
that have turned into safe havens for terrorists could not claim
to be observing international law," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
