<HEADLINE> Egyptian Gulf War Victims to Get Compensations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 13 (Xinhua) -- More than 23,000 Egyptians will
begin receiving on May 3 the first of six installments of U.N. Gulf
War compensation totaling 823 million U.S. dollars, the Egyptian
MENA news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Names of those eligible to receive the checks will be
announced following the Bairam feast holidays, MENA quoted an
official at the Labor and Immigration Ministry as saying.
</P>
<P>
A total of 30,000 Egyptians filed demands claiming compensation
for their departure from Kuwait or Iraq because of the Gulf War,
but 7,000 applications were turned down.
</P>
<P>
The first installment will total 58.3 million dollars, meaning each
person will be receiving between 2,500 and 8,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
On March 19, a U.N. commission handed over 144 million dollars to
63 governments and an international organization which in turn will
distribute the money to nearly 60,000 people affected by Iraq's
1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The funds were made available by an oil-for-food deal signed
last May between Iraq and the U.N. enabling Baghdad to sell 2
billion dollars worth of oil over six months to raise money for
food, medicine and compensation funds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
