<HEADLINE> Former Algerian President Appeals for Talks in Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Former Algerian President Ahmed Ben
Bella today appealed for talks between the Algerian government and
all oppositions, including the outlawed Islamic Salvation Front
(FIS), reported the Agence France-Presse (AFP).
</P>
<P>
In an interview with AFP in Madrid, where he was attending a
non-governmental conference on Algeria, Ben Bella said that
"violence has never been as strong as today" in his country.
</P>
<P>
"The new elections, such as the next legislative elections,
will not solve any problem," said the former president, who
served as Algeria's first head of state after the country won its
independence in 1962 from France.
</P>
<P>
Ben Bella also called for isolation of "extremists in both
camps," and called on Algerian government to launch a "real
dialogue" with all the components of the country's opposition,
including the FIS.
</P>
<P>
"There will be no solution without the participation of FIS
which is a strong party and represents 25-30 percent, if not 40
percent, of the population," he said.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 60,000 to 80,000 people have been killed in
Algeria in the war between Islamic militants and the Algerian
security forces and their militia allies since 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
