<HEADLINE> Sudanese President Returns Home After Visiting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese President Omar
al-Bashir returned home this morning after a three-day visit to
Libya.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese president went to Libya last Friday across
Tunisia without previous declaration by both Sudan and Libya,
with the aim of getting Libyan support for the Sudanese
government in the face of internal conflict in Sudan, a
reliable source here said.
</P>
<P>
Libyan leaders failed to express their view on the
developments in Sudan during the visit by Sudanese First
Vice-President Al-Zubeir Mohammed Saleh to Libya in February.
</P>
<P>
Sudanese rebels have been fighting against government troops
since 1983 for more autonomy in the south.
</P>
<P>
Libya coordinated attitudes with Egypt and considered the
conflict in Sudan an internal affair, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Libya had attempted to act as a mediator between Sudan and
Uganda, and Sudan and Egypt. But it failed to bring foreign
ministers of the three countries together during the Organization
of African Unity (OAU) ministerial meeting in Tripoli, the
capital of Libya, last month.
</P>
<P>
Sudanese media made no mention of the outcome of President
al-Bashir's visit to Libya. Diplomatic sources here speculated
that the talks between the Sudanese and Libyan leaders focused on
bilateral cooperation and issues of mutual concern, including ways
of improving bilateral relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
