<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan, Uganda Hold Talks on Settlement of Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Sudan's President Omar al-Bashir
has held talks with Ugandan Foreign Minister Eriya Kategaya on
ways of settling the Sudan-Uganda border dispute and normalizing
bilateral ties during his recent visit to Libya, the Libyan news
agency (JANA) reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report, monitored here, said that during Sunday's talks
initiated by Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi, the Sudanese president
affirmed that Sudan was willing to settle its differences with
Uganda.
</P>
<P>
On his part, the Ugandan foreign minister stressed Uganda's
willingness to react positively with this initiative for
stabilizing its relations with Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of Libyan General People's Commission for Foreign
Liaison and International Cooperation Omer el-Montasser and
Sudanese Foreign Minister Ali Osman Taha also attended the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The agency added that Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni, who
failed to attend the talks, had a telephone conversation with
Gaddafi, during which the two leaders held consultations on ways
of settling border dispute in central and east Africa through
peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Omer el-Montasser held talks in Tripoli, the
capital of Libya, with foreign ministers of Sudan and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Following the meeting, he told reporters that the two sides
agreed on foundations for settling the dispute between them,
and that positive steps would be taken in the days to come for a
solution to the problem.
</P>
<P>
The Khartoum government repelled an armed attack launched
by the Sudanese opposition forces in eastern and southern Sudan
in mid-January this year. Sudan accused a number of neighboring
states of supporting these forces, but this accusation was denied
by its neighbors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
