<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bhutanese Refugees in Nepal Urge U.N. Intervention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 14 (Xinhua) -- More than 10,000 Bhutanese
refugees gathered at a mass rally in an eastern Nepali town today
to call for U.N. intervention in the Bhutanese refugee issue in
Nepal.
</P>
<P>
The mass rally came after a procession around the town of
Damak, about 200 kilometers from here, with slogans calling for
U.N. intervention.
</P>
<P>
They also demanded that the Nepali government solve the refugee
problem or internationalize it.
</P>
<P>
The Bhutanese refugees at the rally shouted slogans urging
India to stop supporting Bhutan in crushing the refugee movement
for free repatriation.
</P>
<P>
The Bhutanese refugee organization, the Appeal Movement
Coordination Committee (AMCC), on the occasion declared the end of
a relay hunger strike by refugees as the 53rd session of the U.N.
Commission on Human Rights in Geneva approaches its end.
</P>
<P>
The 28-day-long relay hunger strike, launched by the AMCC last
month in a bid to call for a U.N. solution of the Bhutanese
refugee issue, had been participated by more than 15,000 refugees.
</P>
<P>
Lashing out at India's role in deporting Bhutanese refugees to
Nepal by force, an AMCC official told the mass rally that the U.N.
reluctance to see the urgency of the Bhutanese refugee problem in
Nepal will be tantamount to encouraging violence.
</P>
<P>
Around 100,000 Bhutanese refugees, mostly of Nepalese origin,
have been living in various refugee camps in East Nepal since
1990.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
