<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spokesman on Nationalities, Right of Abode of HK Residents (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to the NPC Standing Committee's explanation of
China's Nationality Law, all Hong Kong residents of Chinese
descent, or those who are born in the Chinese territory, including
Hong Kong, and all other people who have Chinese nationality
status under the requirements of China's Nationality Law, are
Chinese citizens.
</P>
<P>
If those who have acquired the right of abode in foreign
countries do not report their foreign nationality, they can travel
to other countries and regions with certificates issued by foreign
governments, but they cannot be under the protection of foreign
consulates in the HKSAR and other regions in China.
</P>
<P>
If these people want to reside in Hong Kong as foreign
residents, they may change their nationality at the Immigration
Department of the SAR by showing valid documents. They will no
longer have Chinese nationality after they obtain the approval to
change citizenship.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that this rule will meet the aspiration of
the broad masses of Hong Kong compatriots to regard themselves as
Chinese, and at the same time, give them the opportunity to choose
any citizenship they prefer while living in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese citizens will acquire the right to live in Hong
Kong according to the stipulations of the Basic Law concerning the
requirements for Chinese, the spokesman said. The non-Chinese
citizens, including those who have obtained approval to change
their nationality, will be granted the right of abode in Hong Kong
according to the stipulations of the Basic Law concerning the
requirements for the non-Chinese citizens, he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman listed six categories of permanent Hong Kong
residents who can enjoy the right of abode in Hong Kong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970414.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
