<HEADLINE> China, Mauritius to Up Bilateral Ties (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng said here
today that China attaches great importance to Sino-Mauritian
relations, and is willing to push bilateral ties up to a new level
through concerted efforts.
</P>
<P>
During talks with visiting Mauritian Prime Minister Navin
Ramgoolam, Li spoke highly of friendship between the two
countries, saying they have established sound co-operative ties in
various fields.
</P>
<P>
It is of great significance that Ramgoolam chose to visit China
at a time when the two countries are celebrating the 25th
anniversary of the establishment of diplomatic relations between
them, Li said, expressing the conviction the visit will further
reinforce the bilateral relationship.
</P>
<P>
Ramgoolam said that 25 years ago, his father, as then prime
minister of Mauritius, forged diplomatic ties with China, and he
himself chose to visit China on this special occasion to show
Mauritius' stress on its relations with China.
</P>
<P>
Mauritius will continue the "one China" policy it has always
been pursuing over the past 25 years, Ramgoolam said, adding that
friendly co-operation between the two nations has been fruitful.
</P>
<P>
Li agreed that since the establishment of diplomatic ties, the
two nations have carried out fruitful economic and trade
co-operation, demonstrating the spirit of "south-south"
co-operation.
</P>
<P>
As a developing country, the Premier noted, China is willing to
continue its economic and trade co-operation with Mauritius
by various means, based on the principle of equality and
mutual-benefit, seeking practical results and common development.
</P>
<P>
Ramgoolam said that as an island country and a free port,
Mauritius, enjoying geographic advantages, is willing to serve as
a bridge between east Asia and Africa. Mauritius and China have
good economic and trade co-operative relations, he noted,
expressing the hope such co-operation will be strengthened. He
also invited China to take part in a series of important projects
Mauritius is planning for development.
</P>
</TEXT>
