<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spokesman on Nationalities, Right of Abode of HK Residents (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
1. A Chinese citizen born in Hong Kong either before or after
the establishment of the Hong Kong SAR has the right of abode in
the region if the child's father or mother had settled in Hong
Kong at the time of or after the child's birth.
</P>
<P>
If only his father is settled in Hong Kong, the child must have
been born to a married couple or have obtained legitimate legal
status.
</P>
<P>
A newborn of Chinese descent who has been abandoned in Hong
Kong, with no evidence to the contrary, can be regarded as a child
born to a married Chinese citizen who has settled in Hong Kong,
and thus has the right of abode in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman explained that the term "settled" can be applied
to anyone who ordinarily resides in Hong Kong and is subject to no
restrictions in terms of duration of residency.
</P>
<P>
2. Chinese citizens who have maintained ordinary residency in
Hong Kong for a continuous period of more than seven years before
or after the establishment of the HKSAR have the right of abode in
Hong Kong. The designated timeframe refers to any continuous
period of seven years before or after the establishment of the
HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the term "ordinary residency," the spokesman
pointed out that if a Hong Kong resident studies or is dispatched
to work outside Hong Kong for a period of time, this time should
be figured into the period of "ordinary residency."
</P>
<P>
But people living in Hong Kong under other circumstances, such
as illegal immigrants, people in prison or those who are being
detained in Hong Kong, foreign laborers or household employees of
foreign nationality, do not have "ordinary residency" status.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970414.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spokesman on Nationalities, Right of Abode of HK Residents (6) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Basic Law grants foreign nationals the right of abode in
Hong Kong, under the prerequisite that they have ordinarily
resided in Hong Kong for a continuous period of not less than
seven years, and also claim that they will live there permanently.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, it is necessary to stipulate that those permanent
Hong Kong residents of non-Chinese nationals, if not residing in
the HKSAR for a continuous period of 36 months at any time, will
lose their status as permanent residents. Exceptions are made for
anyone who has the right of abode only in Hong Kong, or who has
acceptable reasons (such as studying or being sent to work outside
Hong Kong), to stay outside Hong Kong temporarily, while
maintaining a close tie with the region.
</P>
<P>
If anyone with the right of abode only in Hong Kong obtains the
right of abode in another country or region after having obtained
the status of permanent Hong Kong resident, he or she will also
lose the status of permanent Hong Kong resident if he or she does
not reside in the Hong Kong SAR for a continuous period of 36
months at any time after having obtained the right of abode in
another country or region.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also presented an outline for the transitional
arrangements for those who have permanent Hong Kong identity cards
before June 30, 1997.
</P>
<P>
He said that the following people will remain permanent
residents of the HKSAR:
</P>
<P>
-- The Chinese nationals with the status of permanent Hong Kong
residents before the establishment of the Hong Kong SAR, including
those who have moved overseas, but return to and are settled in
Hong Kong after July 1, 1997, while having not applied for foreign
nationality status.
</P>
<P>
-- The non-Chinese nationals with the status of permanent Hong
Kong residents before the establishment of the HKSAR. They can
still be permanent Hong Kong residents so long as they have been
settled in Hong Kong or returned to and been settled in the region
just before June 30, 1997; or they return to and settle down in
Hong Kong within 18 months after July 1, 1997; or they have been
away from Hong Kong only for a successive period of not more than
36 months just before they return and are settled there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970414.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spokesman on Nationalities, Right of Abode of HK Residents (7) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Referring to the settlement in Hong Kong on July 1, 1997,
mentioned in the transitional arrangements, the spokesman said
people are responsible for convincing the Immigration Department
that they have settled in Hong Kong on July 1, 1997, but they do
not have to be in Hong Kong on that day.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also pledged that the right of entry into Hong
Kong will be granted to those non-Chinese nationals who lose the
status of permanent Hong Kong residents due to the above
stipulations and transitional arrangements, in order not to
influence their life and work in Hong Kong. They will be free to
enter and leave Hong Kong, and live and work in the region without
restrictions, he explained.
</P>
<P>
He said the issues of nationalities and the right of abode of
the Hong Kong residents concern the practical interests of
everyone in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Since there are basic laws and policies in this regard, he said
he hopes that the Hong Kong SAR government will work out the
specific stipulations as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also said the Chinese government has always
solicited opinions from the British side while drawing up the
policy on the right of abode of the Hong Kong residents, and still
welcomes the British side to offer its opinions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970414.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spokesman on Nationalities, Right of Abode of HK Residents (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
5. Children, who are under 21 years of age and born in Hong
Kong before or after the establishment of the Hong Kong SAR, of
those permanent residents not of Chinese nationality can have the
right of abode.
</P>
<P>
A Child not of Chinese nationality but born in Hong Kong can
have the right of abode before 21 years of age, if his or her
father or mother has acquired the right of abode in accordance
with the above-mentioned Article 4 when or after the person was
born. The person must be born to a married couple or have acquired
legitimate legal status, if only his or her father has the right
of abode in Hong Kong in accordance with the above-mentioned
Article 4.
</P>
<P>
A newborn of non-Chinese descent who has been abandoned in Hong
Kong, with no evidence to the contrary, can be regarded as having
met the above requirements.
</P>
<P>
People who acquire the status of permanent Hong Kong resident
in accordance with this article should acquire the status of
permanent HKSAR resident by the age of 21, otherwise they will no
longer have the status of permanent HKSAR resident.
</P>
<P>
6. The people other than those listed in Article 1 to 5, who
had the right of abode only in Hong Kong before the establishment
of the HKSAR, can have the right of abode in Hong Kong. They
should make a legal declaration that he or she only had the right
of abode in Hong Kong before the establishment of the HKSAR, and
is responsible for the authenticity of the declaration.
</P>
<P>
The person should be responsible for presenting evidence that
corroborates his or her statement, if he or she is believed to
have the right of abode in another country or region.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the conditions that would result in a person losing
the right of abode in Hong Kong, the spokesman said that according
to the Basic Law of the HKSAR, the permanent residents in the
HKSAR include people either with or without Chinese nationality.
</P>
<P>
After they have obtained the right of abode in Hong Kong,
Chinese citizens shall not lose the right unless they change their
nationality.
</P>
<P>
If they change the nationality, they will be subject to Item
(4) of Clause 2 of Article 24, under which they will lose the
right of abode in Hong Kong if they have not lived in the HKSAR
for a continuous period of seven years immediately before they
change nationalities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970414.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spokesman on Nationalities, Right of Abode of HK Residents (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
3. Children of Chinese nationality born outside Hong Kong to
residents listed in the above two articles will be handled in the
following ways:
</P>
<P>
-- Any child of Chinese nationality born outside Hong Kong
before or after the establishment of the HKSAR have the right of
abode as long as the child's father or mother has the right of
abode in Hong Kong when the child was born;
</P>
<P>
-- If only the father has the right of abode in Hong Kong, the
child must be born to a married couple or have legitimate legal
status.
</P>
<P>
4. Those non-Chinese nationals who enter Hong Kong with valid
travel documents before or after the establishment of the HKSAR,
have ordinarily resided in Hong Kong for a continuous period of
more than seven years and take Hong Kong as their permanent place
of residence will be dealt with in accordance with the following
stipulations:
</P>
<P>
-- The designated timeframe refers to the continuous period of
seven years up to the date just before he or she applies to become
a permanent resident of Hong Kong;
</P>
<P>
-- People not of Chinese nationality must declare that they
will accept Hong Kong as their permanent place of residence in
accordance with legal stipulations, and truthfully report in their
declaration forms personal data which can prove that they will
take Hong Kong as their permanent place of residence. The data
include whether he or she has a place of residence (permanent
residence); whether his or her immediate family members (the
spouse or young children) ordinarily reside in Hong Kong; whether
he or she is legitimately employed or has a stable income; whether
he or she pays taxes in accordance with the Hong Kong laws; and
other related information;
</P>
<P>
-- While scrutinizing the data, the director of the Immigration
Department will deal with the cases in accordance with the
specific conditions of each applicant and is entitled to ask the
applicant, if necessary, to submit supporting documents and
materials. The applicant must be held responsible for the
authenticity of the data.
</P>
</TEXT>
