<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Visits Cairo for Talks with Mubarak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat arrived here at noon today for talks
with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak after the European and
U.S. mediation efforts failed to yield a breakthrough in the
stalemate peace process.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival, Arafat said he will discuss with Mubarak how
to protect the Middle East peace process from collapse. Besides,
they will also tackle economic and financial problems and the
Israeli closure on the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
"We will discuss how to prevent Israel's continued attempts to
violate agreements signed in both Cairo and Washington through
confiscating lands, setting up settlements and Judaizing
Jerusalem," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said he would ask the Egyptian president to exert more
efforts to activate the peace march, which has been stalled since
Israel started building a new Jewish settlement in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's visit came as the separate initiatives proposed by the
U.S. and the European Union (EU) to revive Israeli-Palestinian
talks.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., hosting Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu and
Palestinian envoys in Washington early this month, had apparently
failed to convince Israel to halt the building project, a condition
the Palestinians insist for resuming the talks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Netanyahu only cold-shouldered an EU initiative that
calls on Israel to freeze settlement expansion and Palestinians
to curb violence.
</P>
<P>
Arafat would fly to Valletta, Malta, to attend the
Euro-Mediterranean conference after meeting Mubarak, his longtime
advocate and a critic of the Israeli hardline policy.
</P>
<P>
There he will meet with American Mideast Peace Coordinator
Dennis Ross Tuesday in stepped-up efforts to salvage peace before
U.S. Secretary of State Madeline Albright's scheduled visit to the
region in May.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of Arafat's visit to Cairo, Mubarak said he will
send his political advisor Osama el-Baz to Washington tomorrow at
the request of U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
As no progress has been made in the diplomatic front, violence
continued in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
A Palestinian woman crossing into the West Bank from Jordan
shot and wounded two Israelis and an Arab man Sunday, another
sign of Palestinian frustration over the Jewish housing project
that has touched off almost daily clashes in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
In Hebron, three Palestinians were injured by stones hurled by
Jewish settlers during rock-throwing between the two sides in the
partitioned town in the West Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
