<HEADLINE> Israeli FM to Meet Arafat at Malta Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Israel announced today that
its Foreign Minister David Levy would meet with Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat at Tuesday's Euro-Mediterranean conference
in Malta.
</P>
<P>
Levy decided to attend the two-day conference of the foreign
ministers of the European Union (EU) and 12 Mediterranean
countries, which opens Tuesday, after EU peace envoy Miguel
Angel Moratinos telephoned him that Arafat was interested in
holding a meeting with him, the Israeli Foreign Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The Levy-Arafat meeting will be the first high-level contact
since Israel decided in March to build the Har Homa settlement
in Arab East Jerusalem, which has stalled the peace process. The
two leaders will seek ways of defusing the current crisis and
getting the peace talks back on track.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Foreign Ministry sources said Levy's decision to
attend the conference came only after he got the EU promise that
a resolution denouncing Israel would not be adopted at the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Israel has been strongly criticized for causing the current
Israeli-Palestinian crisis by beginning the building of the Har
Homa settlement. Israeli officials feared the Malta conference
could be exploited as a stage to attack the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Levy met with his Dutch counterpart Hans
Van Mierlo, whose country holds the rotating EU presidency.
</P>
<P>
Mierlo assured that Arab participants had agreed to leave the
Israeli-Palestinian confrontation out of the conference and to
keep the issue out of its resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The EU is currently seeking to strengthen its role in
mediating the Israel-Palestinian peace negotiations so as to
increase its political influence in the region.
</P>
<P>
Israel and the United States have so far rebuffed EU attempts
in this direction, citing that Europe cannot replace the U.S. as
the honest broker in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
However, the two U.S. vetoes of the United Nations Security
Council resolutions slamming Israel's settlement policies have
been widely criticized by the international community, thus
weakening the U.S. role in the peace mediation.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the EU nations, representatives from Algeria,
Cyprus, Egypt, Israel, Jordan, Lebanon, Malta, Morocco, Syria,
Tunisia, Turkey and the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) will
attend the Malta conference, which is supposed to focus on trade
and economic relations.
</P>
<P>
But the conference is overshadowed by the Middle East
politics at a time of rising tension between Israel and Arab
neighbors. Despite the Arab promise to put aside politics,
Israel is still expected to come under harsh criticism in
speeches made by Arab attendants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
