<HEADLINE> China's Air Force to be Equipped with State-of-Art (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese air force plans to
build a new weapon system, equipped with state-of-art early
warning planes, electronic warfare warplanes, and ground-to-air
missiles by early next century, according to the commanding
officer of the air force.
</P>
<P>
"We shall focus our efforts on applying new high-tech to
raising combat effectiveness of the troops while importing some
high-tech weapons which have higher accuracy in hitting the
target," said Lieutenant General Liu Shunyao in an interview with
Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-eight-year-old General Liu was born in Zhaoyuan County in
eastern China's coastal province of Shandong in 1939 and joined
the People's Liberation Army (PLA) in 1958.
</P>
<P>
He became a pilot after he graduated from a flying school of
the air force in 1964. He was conferred the title of lieutenant
general of the airforce in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Since its founding 48 years ago, the Chinese Air Force has
developed into a modernized armed service of the PLA, which
includes combat branches of ground-to-air missiles, antiaircraft
guns, radars, and paratroopers with air units as its main body,
General Liu said.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese air force is now capable of waging high-level
long-distance combats, rapid manoeuvrability, air defense, and
providing assistance to the navy and the ground forces," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Soon after the Chinese Air Force was founded in 1949, it went
to Korea as the air force of the Chinese People's Volunteers to
fight the U.S. invasion and assist the Korean people," he recalled.
</P>
<P>
"During the Korean War (1950-1953) and the national defense of
its own territory over the past 48 years, the Chinese Air Force
altogether has shot down or damaged a total of 3,800 enemy planes,"
General Liu noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
