<HEADLINE> Gulf Overseas Assets Estimated at 350 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Gulf Arab states have an
estimated 350 billion U.S. dollars of overseas assets but some is
expected to flow back to support domestic reforms, a local
newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Al Khaleej on Sunday, Mahammed al Mulla,
secretary general of the Union of Chambers of Commerce and
Industry of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) said the bulk of
the funds were accumulated by the big profits of the oil industry
in the region.
</P>
<P>
The GCC states which group Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the United
Arab Emirates (UAE), Qatar, Bahrain and Oman are abundant in
petroleum deposits and they possess some 60 percent of the
total oil reserves in the world.
</P>
<P>
Mulla said the GCC states hopes that private investment in the
region would increase in the years to come and that overseas assets
would begin to flow back to support the domestic reforms.
</P>
<P>
"GCC states have marched a long way in improving their
investment climate,... we expect a large increase in private
investment in the GCC," the secretary said.
</P>
<P>
The GCC assets abroad are mainly concentrated on real-estate,
stocks and bank deposits in the Western countries.
</P>
<P>
The six countries enjoyed huge abundance of wealth collected
from their oil industry in the oil boom in the late 1970s and
early 1980s when they earned more than 150 billion dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
But This income decreased to about 70 billion dollars a year in
the following years due to a sharp drop in oil prices, which fell
to as low as about 18 dollars per barrel from above 30 dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
