<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Export of 10 Top Products Decreases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The contribution of Indonesia's
10 leading industrial products to total non-oil/gas exports is
decreasing because of their lower competitiveness and
diversification, a monthly report said today.
</P>
<P>
The April report issued by the Ministry of Industry and Trade
said that in 1996 the 10 products -- textiles and products,
leather shoes, wood products, electronic goods, food, paper,
rubber, fish, vegetable oils and toys -- accounted for 83.63
percent of Indonesia's total industrial product exports. In 1995,
they took up 84.31 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, the export value of the 10 commodities amounted to
26.859 billion U.S. dollars in 1996, representing an 8.62-percent
increase over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The growth of the 10 products has also shown a decline in
comparison to the total exportation of industrial products, with a
rise of 9.51 percent last year, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Only electronic goods have registered a higher growth of 30.59
percent between 1995 and 1996, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Electronic export value amounted to 3.256 billion dollars in
1996, up from 2.493 billion dollars in 1995.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
