<DOCNO> XIE19970414.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Euro-Med Cooperation in Hard Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VALLETTA, MALTA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The second
European-Mediterranean conference to be held here Tuesday and
Wednesday can hardly have an easy time as the cooperation between
the two regions has met great challenges.
</P>
<P>
Jean Pierre, the French ambassador for European Union's (EU)
dialog with its southern Mediterranean countries partners said
last week that the Malta conference comes "in a difficult
situation and a hard time."
</P>
<P>
This viewpoint, widely shared among officials and analysts
across the Mediterranean, largely refers to the deadlocked Middle
East peace process and the difficulties arising from the
cooperation launched at the first Barcelona conference 15 months
ago.
</P>
<P>
Just days before the conference, Arab countries expressed
their reservations over a French proposal for a Euro-Mediterranean
"stability pact", on the agenda of the Malta conference, because
it would include Israel.
</P>
<P>
"The arabs unanimously believe that it is premature to speak of
constraining measures and to fix a date for their implementation,"
said Fathi Shazli, An assistant to the Egyptian foreign minister
for European affairs, on behalf of the Arabs.
</P>
<P>
The Barcelona conference put forward two concepts -- namely,
the Euro-Mediterranean partnership and the establishment of a free
trade zone linking the two regions by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
The Malta conference is to be attended by foreign ministers
from EU's 15 members and their 12 Mediterranean partners --
Algeria, Cyprus, Egypt, Israel, Jordan, Lebanon, Malta, Morocco,
Syria, Tunisia, Turkey and Palestine.
</P>
<P>
So far, the EU has concluded bilateral partnership agreements
with six countries and is negotiating with three others. Political
dialogs have been intensified with a frequent exchange of leaders'
visits. European countries, particularly France, have been seeking
active mediation role in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
In the economic field, EU has promised to provide some 5.3
billion U.S. dollars of aid to its Mediterranean partners during
the 1996-2000 period and many of the projects involved are now in
place. The two sides have also set up joint chambers of commerce
and export agencies, and even a Mediterranean bank network.
</P>
<P>
Hailing these achievements, officials and analysts from both
sides acknowledged that they appear to be rather meager in
proportion to the ambitious free trade goal.
</P>
<P>
Major problems found in the existing cooperation include the
wide political and economic disparities between the two sides,
EU's strict limits on agricultural imports and anti-dumping
measures, and a huge trade deficit -- some 185 billion dollars
annually -- on the southern countries' side. Differences in
societies and cultures are also complicating factors.
</P>
<P>
An article carried on the latest issue of Malta Sunday Times
said that the Euro-Mediterranean partnership is "an unequal one,"
heavily biased in favor of the EU.
</P>
<P>
What worries the EU is that some southern Mediterranean
countries are questioning Europe's motives in cooperation, fearing
to be dominated and robbed of profits. Turkey has even threatened
to withdraw from the customs union reached with the EU.
</P>
<P>
To allay these fears, the EU says it will reaffirm Barcelona
conference's goal in Malta and strengthen dialog with its partners.
</P>
<P>
Not alone, these problems will most likely be taken into Malta
discussions together with the faltering Middle East peace process
as widely predicted.
</P>
<P>
It is generally believed that a prerequisite to a full
Euro-Mediterranean cooperation is the increased trade and business
links among the southern countries themselves, which are always
marred and influenced by the political and security situation.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral conflicts are seen in relations between Israel and
Palestine, Israel and Syria, Greece and Turkey as well as
internal problems in Cyprus and Algeria.
</P>
<P>
In protest against Israeli hard-line policy in the Middle East
process, the Arab League made a decision a fortnight ago to
suspend its normalization process of political and economic ties with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Despite all these, politicians and analysts voiced confidence
in achieving success in Malta, saying that the gathering of the
all sides involved around one table itself is great.
</P>
<P>
Still further, observers say, EU's strategy of shifting focus
southwards, together with its poorer southern neighbors' desire
for development, are destined to serve as a joint push to
cooperation and the South-North type dialog like the Malta
conference.
</P>
<P>
Analysts noted that the EU wants to play a bigger role in the
Mediterranean after the end of the Cold War as a counterbalance to
the United States, an idea also favored by the Middle East
countries.
</P>
<P>
An article carried on Britain's Independent Daily early this
month said a good opportunity has arrived for Europe to seek a
more active involvement in the Middle East -- at a time when the
United States gives bias toward Israel in mediation at the cost of
losing Arab countries' trust. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970414.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Launches Reloadable Stored Value Card </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of China (BOC) Group,
Standard Chartered Bank and Visa International today announced the
launch of the reloadable Visa Cash card, representing a big leap
forward in forging an electronic cash payment system in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Not only can card holders make small amount transactions with
the reloadable Visa Cash, but they can also carry out other
financial applications such as credit and debit with just one
card.
</P>
<P>
Card holders will be able to load and unload their cards at the
territory's over 100 designated BOC Group and Standard Chartered
Bank Automatic Telling Machines (ATMs) displaying Visa Cash signs.
The maximum load value each time is 3,000 HK dollars (385 US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
In August 1996, the three institutions joined hands in
launching "Prime Visa Cash", the disposable stored value card
which is a convenient, fast and clean alternative of paying for
smaller value cash items.
</P>
<P>
To date, half-a-million Visa Cash transactions have been
completed with a total value exceeding 15 million HK dollars (1.9
million US dollars). The average transaction value is around 30 HK
dollars.
</P>
<P>
With the launch of the reloadable card, a number of new
merchants have signed up to accept Visa Cash, in addition to the
existing 1,000 merchants, including those from a broad section of
retail and service industries.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference today, the deputy chief executive of
BOC's Hong Kong and Macao Regional Office, Zhang Hongyi, said the
new card brings more efficiency and convenience to the card
holders and participating merchants.
</P>
<P>
And Philippe Paillart, group executive director of Standard
Chartered Bank, said, "Cash purchase transactions therefore march
into a truly coinless generation making purchases more efficient
and become a truly enjoyable experience."
</P>
<P>
Visa Cash eyes a respectable proportion of cash based
transactions, which nowadays make up over 70 percent of total
personal consumption expenditure in Hong Kong, within the next 10
years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
