<DOCNO> XIE19970414.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan President Warns Sudan on War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni has warned that Uganda will give the government of Sudan
a blow if the latter attacks first, "the New Vision" reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Museveni delivered his address last Saturday to the residents
of north-western city of Arua when new conflicts flared in
southern Sudan and near the Uganda-Sudan border.
</P>
<P>
Uganda reinforced its army build-up on its north border to
prevent the spilling over of the war between the rebel Sudan
People's Liberation Army (SPLA) and the government troops
in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by George Willy Odwong, resident district
councilor of Kitgum District, northern Uganda, when he
explained to the residents in the north, responding to the
inquiries for the reason of the increase of the troops in the
border areas.
</P>
<P>
The increase of the troops in the border areas was not yet
confirmed by the army.
</P>
<P>
There are two military conflicts near the Uganda-Sudan border:
one between the Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA) on one hand
and the Sudan government troops and the rebel Lord Resistance
Army (LRA) of Uganda on the other, and another between the
Ugandan government troops and the rebel LRA.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that the SPLA attacked LRA headquaters in
southern Sudan and the government troops of Sudan guarding the
headquaters. The SPLA killed some 150 government soldiers and LRA
members, and captured more than 200 LRA fighters.
</P>
<P>
The LRA is one of the three main rebel groups in Uganda. The
other two are the Allied Democratic Forces (ADF) in the west and
the West Nile Bank Front (WNBF) in the north-west.
</P>
<P>
Both ADF and WNBF had lost their main forces since last
December in their fightings against the government troops of
Uganda and SPLA in southern Sudan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
