<HEADLINE> Aviation Expo/China '97 to be Held in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Aviation Expo/China '97 is to be
held in Beijing from October 8-12, running concurrently with
Airport Expo/China '97, the country's only airport exhibition.
</P>
<P>
Organizers say nearly 300 aviation companies from more than 20
countries and regions, including such industrial giants as
Boeing, Airbus Industrie, and Daimler Aerospace, will take part in
the biennial event to be held in the China International
Exhibition Center.
</P>
<P>
At least six pavilions from China, Australia, France, Israel,
Japan and Britain will join this year's exposition, which is
expected to take up an exhibition area of 10,000 sq.m., according
to the organizers.
</P>
<P>
It will be the seventh Aviation Expo/China held in Beijing. The
event was initiated in 1984 with the approval from the State
Council and co-sponsored by the Civil Aviation Administration of
China (CAAC), Aviation Industries of China and China Council for
the Promotion of International Trade, said Andrew Kay, general
manager of the Hong Kong-based China Promotion Ltd., which
organizes the exposition.
</P>
<P>
He noted that some 1,400 companies from 30 countries have
participated in the exposition since 1984.
</P>
<P>
With China's rapid economic growth and increasing exchanges with
other parts of the world, the airline industry has become one of
the fastest-growing sectors in the country.
</P>
<P>
The industry is expected to score an annual growth of 13
percent by the year of 2000, according to CAAC Director Chen
Guangyi.
</P>
<P>
Last November, China held its first international aviation and
aerospace exhibition in Zhuhai. The show will also be held every
two years in this south city adjacent to Macao.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
