<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Minister Calls for Implementing Population </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Minister for
Population Welfare Abida Hussain today called for implementing the
country's population control programs with greater responsibility.
</P>
<P>
The result-oriented approach was the key to success in
population programs in Pakistan, Abida told a meeting.
</P>
<P>
Strategies will be formulated to ensure effective
implementation of policies on population control at the meeting,
which is jointly organized by the ministry and the United Nations
Fund for Population Activities (UNFPA).
</P>
<P>
Abida stressed the need to appoint those government and
non-government workers who are devoted to work to tackle the
crucial issue of population growth.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Sartaj Aziz, who co-chaired today's meeting,
said it was necessary to make people aware that social and
economic progress could not be accelerated if the population
continues to grow at such a high rate.
</P>
<P>
He said population growth was the most crucial factor retarding
the development of the country.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the UNFPA, international development agencies
and non-governmental organizations are attending the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has a population of about 130 million and its growth
rate is about three percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
