<HEADLINE> Becker Makes Mediocre Comeback, Thai Star Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Boris Becker returned to tournament
play after two-month layoff due to a wrist injury but was beaten
in the doubles here on Monday at the Japan Open tennis tournament.
</P>
<P>
Becker, three-time Wimbledon champion, teaming up with partner
Patrik Kuhen conceded the game to Japanese duo Hiroki Ishii and
Michihisa Onoda 1-6, 7-6 (7-5), 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Becker, second seed here in the men's singles, and the other
top seeds all had first-round byes. He will face Canada's
Sebastien Lareau in the second round Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The German star first hurt his right wrist at Wimbledon last
year, but finished the season as runner-up in the ATP Tour World
Championship and winner of the Grand Slam Cup.
</P>
<P>
This year, he reached the quarterfinals of the Dubai Open two
months ago before withdrawing with his wrist trouble.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's top tennis player Tamarine Tanasugarn, 19, became
the first seed to fall when she crashed to Miho Saeki of Japan in
the women's first round, 3-6, 4-6.
</P>
<P>
Women's top seed American Mary Joe Fernandez withdrew because
of a lower back strain she suffered last week at a tournament in
Florida, the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
