<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Might Continue Its Ban On Imports Of N.Z. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Australia's quarantine
authorities said today it might continue the ban on imports of New
Zealand apples, a move which was welcomed by local growers but
angered its neighbor New Zealand
</P>
<P>
The Australian Quarantine Inspection Service (AQIS) released a
draft pest risk assessment, calling for community and industry
comment before issuing a final report in June.
</P>
<P>
The assessment said apples sourced under the New Zealand
proposal could carry fire blight bacteria, a disease not present
in Australian orchards.
</P>
<P>
"On the basis of those findings, AQIS foreshadowed rejecting
the New Zealand proposal," the AQIS said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Apple and Pear Growers Association said this was
a major win for the industry, worth up to 600 million Australian
dollars (470 million US dollars) a year.
</P>
<P>
Local press reports quoted New Zealand International Trade
Minister Lockwood Smith as saying that the draft recommendation
was extremely disappointing. N.Z. apple growers were expected to
work with their government to determine the next steps including
taking the issue to the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
This is an important case for growers of both countries and it
would be a major decision for the Australian Government to make,
as there is a Closer Economic Relations agreement signed between
them, the reports said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
