<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mechanism Urged to Aid African States in WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of African
Unity (OAU) and the African Economic Community (AEC) today called
for the formation of a permanent institutional mechanism to
support the negotiating capacity of African governments at the
World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
The call came from Assistant Secretary General of OAU/AEC,
Vijay S. Makhan when he was opening a two-day meeting of African
experts on trade policy here.
</P>
<P>
Makhan emphasized that in the new global context of the multi-
lateral trade regime, Africa countries should coordinate their positions
so that their interests be fully reflected in decisions
taken at the WTO.
</P>
<P>
He concluded that such a setup should be proactive and should
help African governments initiate negotiating proposals on trade
issues of common interest to their countries.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is convened to examine the theme "Building the
Capacity of African Governments to Examine the World Trade
Organization (WTO) Negotiations" and to make recommendations on
how OAU/AEC member states could effectively contribute to the
shaping and designing of the rules and regulations governing
international trade relations under the WTO and to engage
effectively in trade negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The African trade experts will be deliberating on the follow-up
to the WTO first ministerial conference held in Singapore in December
last year with particular reference to issues of interest to Africa.
</P>
<P>
They are expected to map out strategies for strengthening
Africa's participation in the WTO negotiations, as well as
building capacities at the national level to address, on a
continuous basis, international trade issues.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is also expected to deliberate the program of
action of the WTO for the least developed countries, trade in
services, specially the proposed multilateral investment
agreement and on other issues on the future negotiating agenda of
the WTO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
