<HEADLINE> India's UF to Choose New Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The 13-party United Front (UF)
will choose a new leader to replace Prime Minister H.D. Deve Gowda
in a bid to form a new government with support from the Congress
party, the Press Trust of India reported today.
</P>
<P>
Front convenor, Andhra Pradesh Chief Minister N. Chandrababu
Naidu, said today the front would choose a new leader at its
Steering Committee meeting in New Delhi on Thursday in view of the
"historical necessity" to continue the coalition government and
block the entry of communal forces (Bharatiya Janata party).
</P>
<P>
"We will select the most suitable candidate (for prime minister
post) from among the front constituents in the interest of
survival of the front government," Naidu told reporters in
Hyderabad, capital of Andhara Pradesh on his return from New
Delhi.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Deve Gowda, who is also leader of the front, had
voluntarily offered to step down to pave the way for new
leadership and keep the front intact, said Naidu, who had played a
key role in installation of the Deve Gowda government last June.
</P>
<P>
Deve Gowda lost a vote of confidence in his government last
Friday in parliament. The Congress party, which withdrew support
for the Deve Gowda government on March 30, has insisted that a
change of leadership in the front is a precondition for the party
to renew its support for the UF.
</P>
<P>
"We (the United Front constituents) have arrived at a consensus
that mid-term elections should be avoided at any cost. There are
no legal hurdles in the way of continuation of the front
government under new leadership," he said.
</P>
<P>
Naidu also clarified that he was not in the race for prime
minister's post. 
</P>
</TEXT>
