<HEADLINE> Test-Tube Baby Born in Chongqing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, April 14 (Xinhua) -- China's newest municipality,
with a population of 30 million, has welcomed the arrival of its
first test-tube baby, and three more are expected to be born this
year.
</P>
<P>
The boy, weighing three kilograms, was born last Thursday at
the Chongqing Woman and Baby Hospital. The mother had been unable
to get pregnant due to blocked fallopian tubes.
</P>
<P>
The hospital pioneers the research of assisted reproductive
technology in southwest China, launching the study in this field
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
It has so far used the technology on 67 women, 27 percent of
whom got pregnant. The hospital said another three test-tube
babies, including a set of triplets, will be born this year.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing is the seventh Chinese city reporting the birth of
test-tube babies, following Beijing, Shanghai, Hangzhou, Shenyang,
Haikou and other cities.
</P>
<P>
More than 250 such babies have been born in these cities since
the first in Beijing in 1988.  
</P>
</TEXT>
