<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anorexia Linked to Brain Deficiency, British Scientists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 14 (Xinhua) -- A British science team has found
anorexia is linked to an abnormality in the brain, the Times
newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Using new scanning techniques, researchers at the London-based
Great Ormond Street Hospital for Children have discovered that 16
out of 18 anorexic children studied reduced blood flow in the part
of the brain that governs visual perception, appetite and sense of
fullness.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that a physical cause has been found for
anorexia. The findings will reassure many parents who fear that
they are to blame for their children's eating disorders.
</P>
<P>
Bryan Lask, a consultant psychiatrist who studied anorexia
patients as young as seven, said that a deficiency in the anterior
temporal lobes, which interpret vision, would explain why
anorexics see themselves as fat when they are thin.
</P>
<P>
Lask said that once the cause of the physical abnormality was
found, pharmaceutical companies would be able to look for the
first medical cure for anorexia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
