<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Work With NGOs in Housing Slum Dwellers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
taken up a comprehensive program to provide permanent housing for
slum dwellers in the country's capital, Dhaka, while trying to
stop the migration of village people to the city, according to a
government official.
</P>
<P>
Telecommunications Minister Mohammad Nasim, who is also in
charge of the Ministry of Public Works, said on Sunday that under
the program, the government would construct multi-story buildings
for the slum people.
</P>
<P>
In the capital of this poor South Asian country, millions of
slum dwellers, most from the rural areas, have been living a
sub-human life in an unhygienic environment.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the multi-story buildings program would start
from the Bashantek slum which was allotted to the poor people by
former President Mujibur Rahman, father of present Prime Minister
Sheikh Hasina.
</P>
<P>
Each genuine slum dweller would be allotted one unit of the
apartments and they could be the owner of the apartment forever
through paying construction cost in installments.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the commitment of the prime minister not to evict
any genuine slum dweller without making alternative arrangement,
the minister said the multi-story buildings would be constructed
in cooperation with non-governmental organizations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
