<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Train Travelers on Decrease in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The number of train travelers was
three percentage points lower in the first quarter of this year
compared with the same period of 1996, latest statistics from the
Ministry of Railways show.
</P>
<P>
In the past three months, trains have carried 227 million
passengers. The figure for March stood at 76.66 million,
representing an 8.1 percent year-on-year decrease.
</P>
<P>
Many travelers in recent years have opted for highway or air
travel to get faster or more comfortable service, resulting in a
smaller market share for railways. In 1996, the number of train
travelers fell by 12.3 percent from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
China's railway departments have taken heed of the downturn in
business and are working to change the situation.
</P>
<P>
As of this month, China's trains increased their speed. On the
three major rail lines of Beijing-Shanghai, Beijing-Guangzhou, and
Beijing-Harbin, trains' per-hour speed reached 140 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
A total of 78 overnight trains are now running between large
and medium-sized cities, with a distance within 1,500 km, in an
effort to make train travel more convenient.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, railway departments are improving service and
promoting market sales, such as ensuring the supply of clean water
and reasonably priced food.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Railways say that the past three months were
all listed as "Safety Months" for railways, with no train
accidents reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
