<HEADLINE> Nigerian Government Stops Campaigns for Abacha </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The federal government of Nigeria
has issued a stern warning and urged for an immediate halt to
calls for the candidature of Head of State General Sani Abacha in
the country's the presidential election next year.
</P>
<P>
As the first official reaction to the campaigns, Minister of
Special Duties Alhaji Wada Nas said in a two-page statement last night
that the media advertisements might cast doubt in Nigerians about the
government's true intentions in the transition program.
</P>
<P>
"These advertisements have consequently generated a belief among
unsuspecting Nigerians either that they are being sponsored by the
government or are done with its knowledge and approval," he said,
quoted by press reports today.
</P>
<P>
Reports on calls from some government officials, politicians, and
religious and traditional leaders on Abacha to run for the presidency
have been increasing in the media of the country since late last year,
along with those on opposite views.
</P>
<P>
The latest surge in the campaign followed a call recently by Chief
Press Secretary to the head of state, Chief David Attah, that pressure
be mounted on Abacha to run.
</P>
<P>
But the minister said the government has nothing to do with such
activities which are "prejudical to the integrity of the political
transition program".
</P>
<P>
Abacha himself has parried the issue. In an interview with the U.S.
daily Washington Times two months ago, he said he had not given
thought to it and the decision on his candidature was his
"constituency's".  
</P>
</TEXT>
