<HEADLINE> Police Attacked By Petrol Bombs In Belfast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Police in north Belfast were
attacked by petrol bombs on Sunday in a second night of fighting
between rival gangs, BBC Television reported.
</P>
<P>
Officers of Royal Ulster Constabulary (RUC), state police force
in Northern Ireland, moved in when a 30-strong crowd gathered
around midnight on Timestone Road, a dividing line between
Catholic and Loyalist areas.
</P>
<P>
A RUC spokesman said five petrol bombs were thrown at the
police officers during the "minor disturbances," the report said.
</P>
<P>
No one was injured in the attack and no arrest has been made
for a public order offense. 
</P>
</TEXT>
