<DOCNO> XIE19970414.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 09:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Airline Suffers Huge Loss in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 14 (Xinhua) -- the Israeli airline (EL AL), is
reportedly to have suffered an 80-million-US-dollar loss in 1996,
which could harm the Israeli government's intention to begin the
company's privatization process this year.
</P>
<P>
Today's Jerusalem Post quoted sources from the company as
saying that the poor performance is due to external factors and
not internal company inefficiencies.
</P>
<P>
According to El Al, an 30 percent increase in fuel costs and
the decline in numbers of tourists in a year because of heightened
terrorist activity are the main reasons for the loss, which will
formally announced by the company in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
This is still a better end-of-year picture than that forecast
by general manager Yoel Feldschuh, who in last October predicted a
100-million-US-dollar loss for 1996.
</P>
<P>
In order to offset the anticipated loss, El Al cut 20
percent of its planned winter schedule, and increased layoffs
of seasonal employees.
</P>
<P>
"We are optimistic of an improved situation this year," said
company spokesman Nachman Klieman, adding that "there are signs of
an increase in tourism, and we already have large numbers of
bookings from Israelis traveling abroad."
</P>
<P>
Israelis comprise more than 50 percent of El Al's overall
market, a change from previous years, when foreigners made up
the bulk of the airline's customers.
</P>
<P>
Since the Israeli government demand that El Al make every
effort to be break-even, the 80-million-US-dollar loss will be a
blow to the prime minister's office and transport ministry, which
are intent on privatizing the company as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Talks among El Al, the transport ministry and government
companies authority are said to be near completion, but many
close to the talks believe an imminent flotation is a
pipe-dream.
</P>
<P>
Among the problems envisaged are the insistence of Transport
Minister Yitzhak Levy that the company not be allowed to fly on
Shabbat, no matter who owns the airline.
</P>
<P>
The workers and the company executives have held a series of
meetings to discuss the problem of unemployment after the company
being privatized.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the workers have been seeking independent
advice on the possibility of purchasing shares in El Al in any
future flotation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a government committee on selling El Al, which
should have made its recommendations by mid-January, has still
not reached an agreement as to the nature of the privatization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
