<HEADLINE> Coastal Erosion Serious in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Coastal erosion nation-wide
in Malaysia has reached an "alarming stage" with the number of
problem sites increasing over the last 12 years.
</P>
<P>
Until the end of last month, 74 sites have been identified as
having serious problems, Neo Tong Lee, director general of the
Irrigation and Drainage Department under the Ministry of
Agriculture, said today while opening a seminar on sustainable
development of the coastal zone in Petaling Jaya near here.
</P>
<P>
"This situation is alarming because the number of sites
identified has increased compared to only 47 in 1985 when the
National Coastal Erosion study was conducted," he was quoted by
the Malaysian national news agency Bernama as saying.
</P>
<P>
The erosion was mainly caused by poor siting, planning and
design of coastal development projects, he said quoting the
finding of the study, adding that to tackle the problem, the
government has allocated 400 million ringgit (about 160 million
U.S. dollars) this year for coastal erosion-control works.
</P>
<P>
The official said the study also revealed that some 1,290
kilometers or 29 percent of the Malaysian coastline was subjected
to erosion.
</P>
<P>
"The finding is highly alarming and disturbing for which short
and long term measures have been recommended for implementation,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Long term strategies for proper planning, regulation and
control of future development in coastal zone are needed so as not
to aggravate existing problems or create new ones, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Neo, the government's efforts in coastal zone
planning include the National Coastal Zone Management Project
under the Danish Cooperation on Environment and Development
Project which involves the drafting of an Integrated Coastal Zone
Management Plan for States of Pulau Pinang, Sabah and Sarawak as
pilot projects.
</P>
<P>
The project is expected to generate further impetus for similar
studies in the other states, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
