<HEADLINE> Manila to Review Trade Dispute With Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is
seriously considering seeking a review of the 121.5 percent
countervailing duty imposed by Brazil on Philippine exports of
desiccated coconut, the Presidential Palace said today.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Trade and Industry informed President Fidel
Ramos that it was considering this option after the Dispute
Settlement Body formed by the World Trade Organization (WTO) ruled
in favor of Brazil.
</P>
<P>
The dispute arose from Brazil's decision in August 1995 to
impose the countervailing duty, claiming that the Philippines
subsidized its desiccated coconut exports to the detriment of
Brazil's domestic industry, the Palace said.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines had earlier disputed the Brazilian claim and
challenged the countervailing duty before the Dispute Settlement
Body under WTO law.  
</P>
</TEXT>
