<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia's Largest Gifts, Premium Shows Open in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong giftware industry
is expecting a gift for themselves this year with rising demands
from major markets, an industry leader, Jeffrey Lam, said here
today.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking on the opening day of Asia's largest gifts and
premium trade fairs -- the 12th Hong Kong Gifts and Houseware Fair
and the 7th Hong Kong Premium Show.
</P>
<P>
Larger than ever, the two-in-one event has attracted a record
high of 1,570 gifts and premium companies from 34 countries and
regions.
</P>
<P>
Overseas participation, in particular, registered a remarkable
31 percent increase over last year, with the number exceeding 580
companies.
</P>
<P>
Lam, who chairs the organizing committee of the Gifts and
Houseware Fair, said, after a year of modest growth, the industry
is expecting a better prospect for 1997.
</P>
<P>
"We expect a six to eight percent growth this year with surging
consumer spending in the United States, our biggest market.
Teaming with rising demand for all kinds of giftware and household
products in the booming Asia-Pacific region, there are every signs
of optimism for the industry," he said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Hong Kong exported 295 billion HK dollars (37.8
billion US dollars) of gifts, premiums and household goods, while
imports also reached 234 billion HK dollars (30 billion US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The United States absorbed over 35 percent of the territory's
gifts exports, followed by Japan, Germany, the Chinese mainland
and Britain.
</P>
<P>
The Gifts and Houseware Fair is organized by the Hong Kong
Trade Development Council (TDC), and the Premium Show is jointly
organized by the TDC and the Hong Kong Exporters' Association.
</P>
<P>
Besides taking up the entire six levels of exhibition space at
the Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Center, the twin fairs,
also expanded to cover the exhibition hall at the nearby Hong Kong
Exhibition Center.
</P>
<P>
Expected to receive 32,000 buyers, the four-day events featured
all kinds of innovative gift items, household products, premiums
for promotion, advertising and souvenir purposes, including home
furnishings, watches and clocks, kitchenware, stationery,
decorative items, electronic appliances and toys.  
</P>
</TEXT>
