<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Egypt Not Happy with Israel's Attitude </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and Egypt today
expressed their dissatisfaction over the attitude of Israel's
leader Benjamin Netanyahu towards peace in West Asia.
</P>
<P>
Briefing the press on the talks here today between Malaysian
Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad and his Egyptian counterpart Kamal
Ahmed El-Ganzouri, Malaysian foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad
Badawi said that the two leaders "expressed dissatisfaction over
the attitude of the Israeli leader towards peace in that region."
</P>
<P>
Both prime ministers had similar perception on the West Asia
issue and felt that the peace process there must move forward as
it was very important for both the Palestinians and Israelis,
Abdullah said.
</P>
<P>
On enhancing bilateral trade and economic relations, Abdullah
said the initiatives taken towards this end were the signing of
the Investment Guarantee Agreement, Avoidance of Double Taxation
and the Prevention of Fiscal Evasion in respect of Taxes on
Income, the Air Transport Agreement, and Memorandums of
Understanding on Trade Promotion and Tourism today.
</P>
<P>
He said both prime ministers felt that private sectors of both
countries must play their roles by entering into joint ventures in
efforts to improve cooperation in economic and trade fields.
</P>
<P>
He said the talks focused on areas of cooperation such as air
services, tourism, manufacturing, agriculture particularly
agro-based industries, collaboration in cultivation of cotton and
manufacturing of cotton-based products and also palm oil.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian prime minister arrived here last night on a
three-day official visit to Malaysia. He will leave here for
Singapore tomorrow.  
</P>
