<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai: China's Biggest Flower Consumer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Flowers are becoming an
important part of life for the residents of Shanghai, which has
been listed as the country's biggest flower consumer for the past
few years.
</P>
<P>
The annual fresh flower sales in China's largest city comes to
270 million bouquets, making up a third of the country's flower
market, figures show.
</P>
<P>
Just a few years ago, buying fresh flowers was a luxury in the
eyes of ordinary residents. People went to flower markets mainly
at festival time or on special occasions, and the varieties were
limited to carnations, roses and chrysanthemums.
</P>
<P>
With the growth of the country's flower planting area, the
number of flowers for sale has soared, and there are now more than
40 different types of locally planted flowers alone. Over 3,000
flower shops scatter throughout the city's streets and residential
areas.
</P>
<P>
The prosperity of the flower market has led to a drop in
prices, making it possible for more and more residents to enjoy
the fresh fragrant blossoms.
</P>
<P>
"Many people have gotten into the habit of buying one bouquet
of fresh flower every time they go shopping," said a flower
dealer. "It's fashionable to take a bouquet of flowers to a
hospital patient, or when going to a party."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, people are becoming increasingly discriminating
about their flower buying: statistics show that the sales of
high-quality imported flowers account for a third of the total in
the city's two major flower markets.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the flower planting industry has become a "ready
source of money" for Shanghai. Official figures reveal the city
has earned more than 10 million US dollars through flower export
every year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
