<HEADLINE> Oppositions Call for Tightening Sanctions on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Burundi's opposition parties
have called for the continuation of sanctions against their
country ahead of a regional summit on Burundi to be held this
week, the East African reported today.
</P>
<P>
The weekly newspaper said that the oppositions made the call
when they met Great Lakes mediator Julius Nyerere last Saturday
in Tanzania's northern city of Arusha.
</P>
<P>
The heads of state and government of Cameroun, Ethiopia,
Kenya, Rwanda, Uganda, Zaire, Zambia and host Tanzania are
scheduled to hold a regional summit in Arusha on April 16 to
review the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
A delegate to the meeting with Nyerere said, "conditions are
still not favorable to lift the sanctions."
</P>
<P>
He noted that people are still kept in camps, political
parties are not allowed to operate freely and the parliament is
still not operating well in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
The Tutsi-dominated Burundi government led by Pierre Buyoya
pledged in February this year to hold talks with his opponents
unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions against Burundi imposed by the regional states
are aimed at forcing the junta leader, who seized power last
July, to quit, and getting the rival sides to negotiate an end to
the three-and-a-half year war between the minority Tutsi-led army
and Hutu rebels. 
</P>
