<DOCNO> XIE19970414.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Behind Pakistan's Wheat Supply Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan has been facing an
acute wheat flour shortage for a few months. However, the crisis
of wheat scarcity still persists despite some emergency measures
taken by the government to stabilize the situation.
</P>
<P>
Wheat flour, the main ingredient used by the Pakistanis in
making their staple diet, is still being sold at a price much
higher than what has been fixed by the authorities.
</P>
<P>
People standing in long queues at major flour shops in
different cities trying to get the hardly available commodity has
almost been a national phenomenon these days.
</P>
<P>
Millions of people have been affected by the wheat shortage
brewing since the middle of January this year. There have been
incidents in the last few weeks of angry citizens looting utility
stores and even snatching flour bags from government trucks and
private shops.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the crisis has set off a fresh price spiral
especially in the northern regions, with hoarders and
blackmarketeers selling the commodity at almost double the
official rate.
</P>
<P>
The shortage, however, is expected to be eased with the start
of wheat crop harvest and arrival of about ten shiploads in the
country before the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
Government sources believe that the recent wheat crisis has
been mainly attributed to the hoarding of wheat by businessmen and
traders, and smuggling of the commodity to Afghanistan and Central
Asian states for higher profits. This has created a somewhat
"artificial shortage."
</P>
<P>
Analysts here noted that the recent wheat supply crisis has
also brought to light some long-standing problems facing
Pakistan's agricultural sector, including lower productivity,
inconsistent implementation of government policies and lower
enthusiasm of farmers.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's economy depends primarily on agriculture. The sector
contributes the largest share to the GDP which was estimated at 25
percent in 1995-96 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
However, despite being an agricultural country, Pakistan's
imports of various major food items have been increasing in the
last few years.
</P>
<P>
As far as wheat is concerned, Pakistan's total annual
requirement is estimated to be at 20 million tons. However, wheat
production last year was only 16.82 million tons, much below the
estimate.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the wheat acreage is also reported to have gone down
by five to six percent mainly in the irrigated areas of Sindh and
Punjab.
</P>
<P>
The import of food items amounted to 1.07 billion US dollars in
the last fiscal year, which was the largest ever in terms of
value. The imported food items include edible oil, wheat, tea,
milk and cream, sugar and even vegetables such as potatoes and
onions.
</P>
<P>
As against the imports, the foreign exchange earnings through
exports of food items such as rice, fish and fish preparations,
fruit and vegetables in the last fiscal year was only about 716
million dollars, indicating an adverse balance of about 300
million dollars in the imports and exports of food items.
</P>
<P>
Thus, Pakistan has been a net importer of food items despite
being an agricultural country. Local economists are of the view
that there is an urgent need to inject dynamism in Pakistan's
vital agricultural sector.
</P>
<P>
And to solve the wheat shortage on a more permanent basis, at
least two basic factors should be taken into consideration. One is
to increase per acre yield, and the other is to increase the
support price of wheat to a level where its production is not
squeezed out by any other crop.
</P>
<P>
To increase the per acre yield in various food crops, which is
much lower than the neighboring countries, is believed to be the
most imminent task facing the government.
</P>
<P>
For this purpose the search for new policy directions for
injecting dynamism in agriculture will have to take into account
the urgent need for accelerating research and development.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, farmers should be able to have increased access to
financing facilities for purchasing inputs, machinery and other
items besides financing for marketing their produce.
</P>
<P>
The government led by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, which came
to power in mid-February, has emphasized the need to give top
priority to the development of agriculture sector.
</P>
<P>
The increase in the procurement price of wheat announced by the
government of Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif in the agricultural
package early this month will help boost wheat cultivation.
</P>
<P>
However, the problem of increasing the per acre yield of wheat
will not be solved in a short period of time. It needs consistent
efforts by government, farmers as well as researchers for a better
situation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970414.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
