<HEADLINE> Canadians Record Two Wins in Curling World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Canada collected two victories
while the Americans suffered two losses in the women's events at
the World Curling Championships in Bern, Switzerland on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Sandra Schmirler, five months pregnant, paced the Canadians to
defeat Norway 5-3 in the morning before routing the United States
9-4 in the evening.
</P>
<P>
The Canadians rallied from 2-4 after the fourth end to overturn
the scoreboard by scoring a triple in the fifth, marching forward
along their voyage for a third world title.
</P>
<P>
Yet, their bid was blunted as Jan Betker suffered a strain to
her thigh muscle.
</P>
<P>
In other matches, Germany, led by skip Andrea Schoepp, crushed
Scottish foursome 10-3, Norway, the world champion in 1990 and
1991, defeated host Switzerland 7-5, Denmark savored a 11-4 win
over Japan and Sweden outscored Finland 7-4.
</P>
<P>
Canada, Germany and Denmark topped the standings with two
straight wins. 
</P>
