<DOCNO> XIE19970414.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chang lifts Third Salem Open Hong Kong Tennis Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 14 (Xinhua) -- It was just 45 seconds that
decided the winner of what the tournament director described as
"the most unusual final in the eight years of the Salem Open
tennis tournament" here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
And it was top seed Michael Chang of the United States that won
the rain-delay men's singles final against Australia's Patrick
Rafter at the 328,000 U.S. dollars 1997 Salem Open.
</P>
<P>
Chang led 6-3, 5-3 and had two match points on his serve in
hand overnight after a heavy shower halted play on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
When the final resumed Monday morning, the fifth-seeded
Rafter, now ranked 43rd in the world, won the first point with an
overhead smash but then his backhand return was too long on the
next point. Chang thus sealed his victory 6-3, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
Tournament Director Michael Luevano said the final was probably
the first one that has been delayed overnight by rain with a
player holding two match points.
</P>
<P>
But Chang had already showed his form on Sunday with a great
display of baseline tennis.
</P>
<P>
Martin Damm Daniel Vacek of Czech Republic beat Karsten Braasch
of Germany and Jeff Tarango of the United States to take the men's
doubles title.
</P>
<P>
"I do not know how many times I thought about the match last
night," said Chang, winner of the annual Hong Kong event in 1994
and 1995.
</P>
<P>
"There were so many things going through my mind -- should I
hit it to his backhand, should I slice it or serve and volley.
</P>
<P>
"It is strange to have so much time to think about a match,
especially when the first few points are so important. If I lost
them it could have been a turning point in the whole match," he
continued.
</P>
<P>
Chang then mentioned a moment early Monday morning when he
watched television coverage of the U.S. Masters golf championship
where his compatriot Tiger Woods scored a record victory.
</P>
<P>
"He is quite incredible -- it made me think a bit about me
winning the French Open at 17 and how professionals accomplish
things so young. I had the feeling Tiger Woods did not quite know
what was going on and it was like that for me at the French. It
was only afterwards that I realized the significance," said Chang,
winner of the French Open in 1989 at the age of 17 years and three
months.
</P>
<P>
Rafter said that he tried to be calm when remaining part of the
final match resumed this morning.
</P>
<P>
"I just tried to be relaxed but it was over quickly," said
Rafter. "I had my chances yesterday but did not take them. He
took his chances and that is why he is where he is," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
