<HEADLINE> India's Federal Front Opposes Move to Dissolve House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 14 (Xinhua) -- In a significant development,
India's Federal Front on Sunday openly came out against any move
to dissolve the Lok Sabha (the lower house of parliament) and hold
fresh elections, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
A joint statement to this effect issued by the leaders of the
four regional parties assumed significance in the wake of a strong
move by a section of the United Front (UF) leaders favoring
dissolution of the Lok Sabha to pave the way for mid-term polls
following the government led by Prime Minister H.D. Deve Gowda
lost a vote of confidence last Friday.
</P>
<P>
"After a review of the events, subsequent to the withdrawal of
support to the UF government by the Congress party, the Federal
Front leaders have not favored the dissolution of the 11th Lok
Sabha," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The four regional parties of the Federal Front, part of the
ruling 13-party United Front, are the Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam
(DMK), Tamil Maanila Congress (TMC), Telugu Desam Party (TDP) and
Asom Gana Parishad (AGP).
</P>
<P>
As the general elections last year resulted in a hung
parliament, the four regional parties have played a major role in
the formation of the UF.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Front will still play a decisive role in any new
political realignment following the Deve Gowda government's defeat
in the vote of confidence.  
</P>
</TEXT>
