<DOCNO> XIE19970414.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Egypt Sign Investment Guarantee Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and Egypt today
signed an Investment Guarantee Agreement aimed at expanding and
deepening economic and industrial cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, signed in witness of Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad and his Egyptian counterpart Karmal Ahmed
El-Ganzouri, provides for a framework to further expand the flow
of investment and business activities between Malaysia and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, signed here by Malaysian International Trade and
Industry Minister Rafidah Aziz and Egyptian Trade and Supply
Minister Ahmed A. Gewili, protects investments by investors of
both countries made prior to as well as after the signing of the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
It also addresses the concerns of investors about expropriation
and nationalization and repatriation of investment in terms of
free transfer of income accruing to investment.
</P>
<P>
It also covers settlement of dispute through the International
Center for Settlement of Investment Dispute (ICSID) or the
Arbitration of the International Chamber of Commerce or
International Ad-hoc Arbitral Tribunal established under the
Arbitration Rules of the United Nations Commission on
International Trade Law.
</P>
<P>
At present, only one Malaysian company -- Sime-Darby Edible
Oils Products -- invested in Egypt while Egypt has no investment
in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's bilateral trade with Egypt amounted to only 625
million Ringgit (about 250 million U.S. dollars) in 1996,
representing 0.2 per cent of Malaysia's total trade, with exports
from Malaysia to Egypt amounting to 606 million Ringgit (about
242.4 million U.S. dollars) while imports from Egypt totaling 19
million Ringgit (about 7.6 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Major Malaysian exports to Egypt were palm oil, natural rubber,
television receivers, paper and paper board while major imports
from Egypt were mainly fruits and nuts, floor covering, spices and
textile yarn.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian prime minister arrived here last night for a
three-day official visit.
</P>
<P>
He will leave for Singapore tomorrow after the visit here.
</P>
</TEXT>
