<HEADLINE> 72 Taliban Killed in West Afghanistan: Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Seventy-two Taliban soldiers
were killed and 41 others wounded during fighting in the western
Afghan province of Badghis.
</P>
<P>
The forces of the anti-Taliban alliance have been advancing
toward the Badghis capital of Kala-i-Now, about 500 kilometers
west of Kabul, since Saturday night, reports reaching here said
today.
</P>
<P>
There have also been reports of exchange of heavy fire between
the warring groups in the area north of Kala-i-Now, but no figures
of losses and casualties were available.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the anti-Taliban forces have gained more territory
in southeastern Parwan Province in the past two days.
</P>
<P>
Ahmad Masood, former military chief of the ousted Afghan
President Burhanuddin Rabbani, has threatened that the
anti-Taliban alliance would launch a coordinated offensive against
the Islamic student militia.
</P>
<P>
"In a couple of days we will have a meeting in which we will
create a unified command center," Masood said last weekend at a
town in northern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
He said the alliance, composed of his own force and troops of
northern warlord Rashid Dustam and Hezb-e-Wahdat leader Karim
Khalili, was preparing to open a new front with combined offensive
against the Taliban, which were already "overstreched" on several
fronts.
</P>
<P>
There had been no such coordination in the past in the
anti-Taliban alliance, Masood said, adding that this was why the
Taliban were able to make such dramatic gains north of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
"This year, all our groups will begin fighting from several
directions simultaneously," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
