<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Sees More Areas for Cooperation With China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Deputy Finance
Minister Wong See Wah said today that there are more possible
areas for investment in Malaysia by Chinese businessmen.
</P>
<P>
These include resource-based industries if Malaysia's natural
resources such as rubber, timber, palm oil and clay could be
utilized for downstream processing, he told reporters after
meeting with visiting Chinese Vice Finance Minister Xie Xuren
here.
</P>
<P>
Other areas are agro-based industries such as cultivation of
fruits and vegetables and the breeding, rearing and culturing of
livestock and aquatic products, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also cited industrial machinery and equipment such as
machinery and machine tools for metal working and wood working as
potential areas.
</P>
<P>
Besides, he said, the Chinese could also venture into ancillary
and supporting industries to provide the necessary linkages to the
established larger industries such as the manufacture of molds and
dies.
</P>
<P>
At present, the investment from China in Malaysia is in areas
like chemical, electrical, electronic and rubber products.
</P>
<P>
There were a total of 44 projects in the manufacturing sector
with Chinese investment amounting to more than 610 million
ringgit (about 244 million U.S. dollars) between 1989 and 1996,
which Wong said was relatively low.
</P>
<P>
He said that "the Chinese have also shown interest in the
operations of the Labuan International Offshore Finance Center and
Multimedia Super Corridor in Malaysia."
</P>
<P>
He also said there exists potential for Malaysia to increase
exports to China, which has a huge market potential for Malaysia's
products such as palm oil, rubber and timber.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Xie Xuren, who is on an eight-day visit to Malaysia,
told reporters that he is keen to learn about the fiscal
relationship between Malaysia's federal and local governments and
the management of government expenditure which is under the
jurisdiction of the Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
He said his delegation is also interested in Malaysia's rice
management and purchasing policies, which are under the auspices
of the Agriculture Ministry.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
