<HEADLINE> New Generation of Scientists Play Major Roles in Tianjin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, April 14 (Xinhua) -- A number of young scientists in
China's north port city of Tianjin are now reaching maturity, as a
result of the municipality's "cross-century talent project".
</P>
<P>
Starting in 1995 Tianjin selected 145 excellent young leading
scientists and gave them special attention and assistance in
provision of funds and facilities. This was named the
"cross-century talent project."
</P>
<P>
These young scientists have been involved in nearly 200 key
research projects, and made nearly 100 scientific discoveries
among which 46 won awards from related departments of the central
and provincial governments.
</P>
<P>
Some of these scientific findings have been turned into huge
economic benefits. A new cucumber strain named "Jinchun NO.4"
developed by several young scientists, for example, have created
a direct economic benefit of more than eight million yuan (nearly
1 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The "cross-century talent project" is also believed to have
greatly improved the young scientists' academic level and
researching ability.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, some 80 papers written by the 145
selected young scientists have been published in national academic
journals, and more than 90 papers presented at national or
international seminars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
