<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leftist Party to Continue Peace Talks with Manila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' major leftist
party, the National Democratic Front (NDF), will continue its
peace talks with the government this month, local press reports
said today.
</P>
<P>
The talks between the NDF and the government next week in the
Netherlands will proceed despite obstructions from some members of
the government peace panel, NDF leader Jose Sison was quoted as
saying in a statement sent to media groups here.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed last month to continue the next round of
talks this month to discuss three important items leading to an
agreement on human rights in June this year.
</P>
<P>
During the coming peace talks, Sison said, the government and
NDF reciprocal working committees will complete the drafting of
the comprehensive agreement on human rights and international
humanitarian law from April 18 to 21.
</P>
<P>
On April 22, the two sides will sign certain short agreements
on security of personal in consultations and initial the
comprehensive agreement on human rights and international
humanitarian law.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will also begin to draft agreements on social and
economic reforms from April 23 to 27, said Sison, who has lived in
exile in the Netherlands since the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
The NDF has been opposing the government since it was created
by the Philippine Communist Party in the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
The NDF had been one of the country's major anti-government
forces in the 1980s, with its military wing, the New People's
Army, operating all over the country.
</P>
<P>
But the NDF's strength was weakened considerably after the
government stepped up its crackdown on the New People's Army in
the late 1980s, forcing some NDF leaders to flee to the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The NDF, which began its first exploratory peace talks with the
government in 1992, resumed its peace talks with the government in
January after four years of suspension.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
