<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Boy Survives Liver Transplantation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 14 (Xinhua) -- A 12-year-old Chinese boy who
underwent a liver transplant, has now returned to school, 320 days
following the operationa.
</P>
<P>
Doctors said his survival period is the longest among Chinese
patients who suffered from Wilson's disease and received
transplants.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Xi was near-death last May when he was diagnosed with
Wilson's disease, or hepatolenticular degeneration, which leads to
hepatic failure, cirrhosis of the liver, ascites, and ultimately
death.
</P>
<P>
Doctors of the Changzheng Hospital in Shanghai performed the
transplant on May 22, 1996. He was in intensive care for 60 days,
and pulled through a number of near-fatal post-operative
complications, such as transplant rejection.
</P>
<P>
Zhang's transplanted organ has functioned normally since his
discharge from the hospital last September, according to the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
A nine-year-old girl in Shanghai who underwent a liver
transplant about three months ago is believed to be the youngest
liver transplant recipient in China, an expert on liver
transplants told Xinhua in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
More than 20 hospitals in Shanghai, Tianjin, Beijing, Wuhan and
Guangzhou reportedly have conducted liver transplants since the
first surgery was done in China in 1973. One of the patients has
survived for about two years, he said.
</P>
<P>
"However, compared with foreign countries, China still lags
behind in the field of transplant surgery," said Professor Zhang
Kaizhi in Beijing Anzhen Hospital.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
