<HEADLINE> Local Cyclist Wins Paris-Roubaix Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Local entry Frederic Guesdon became
a surprising winner here on Sunday by beating World Cup champion
Johan Museeuw to take the 266-km Paris-Roubaix cycling race.
</P>
<P>
The 25-year-old Guesdon, who finished just 14th last season,
breezed past Belgium's Jo Planckaert and overall World Cup
champion Johan Museeuw on the final bend to take the classic event
by a length.
</P>
<P>
France's Frederic Moncassin and Ukrainian Andrei Tchmil,
leaders over the last 15km, were caught up on entering the
velodrome for a sprint finish.
</P>
<P>
Guesdon said afterwards: "I had the sprint of my life and it
succeeded. I was lucky to finish because I started badly after
puncturing in the first paved section."
</P>
<P>
Guesdon, a professional for two years, joined the Francaise des
Jeux team in the close season.
</P>
<P>
France's Ludovic Auger and Italy's Fabrizio Guidi were taken to
hospital for fractured collarbones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
