<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Chancellor Vows to Meet Euro Targets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 13 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl vowed
today that Germany will meet the criteria in time to qualify for
the single European currency, the Euro.
</P>
<P>
In a keynote address opening the world's largest industrial
trade fair in Hanover, Kohl said Germany would make the first wave
to join the Euro and the scheduled January 1, 1999 start date of
the single currency would be adhered to.
</P>
<P>
Although doubted by many leading experts, including two top
government economic advisers and Germany's central bank, Kohl said
he still believed that Germany would be able to meet one of the
key Euro targets which requires a member state to bring its budget
deficit under 3 percent of its gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the realization of the European Monetary Union
and the Euro is a central building block for the construction of a
common Europe.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that such a Europe would not do without the
participation of Britain. "I cannot imagine a house of Europe in
which there is no apartment for the British," Kohl said.
</P>
<P>
The Hanover Fair, which celebrates its 50th anniversary this
year, will be formally opened to the public on Monday. With 7,259
exhibitors over more than 270,000 square meters of exhibition
ground, the show is expected to attract 300,000 visitors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
