<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The paper frontpaged a story about the efforts made by the
grain purchasing departments in northeast China's Heilongjiang and
Jilin provinces to preserve vast quantities of purchased grain.
</P>
<P>
Last year grain output in the two provinces totaled 53.25
billion kg, among which 34 billion kg needed to be purchased and
shipped to other placed of the country.
</P>
<P>
-- Construction work on the Xiaolangdi key water control
project in the middle reaches of the Yellow River, the second
longest river in China, has been speeded up to guarantee the
damming of the river as scheduled on October 31 this year.
</P>
<P>
Also the relocation of residents in the dam area is well
underway. To date 20,000 people of more than 7,000 households have
been relocated to new places.
</P>
<P>
-- A spokesman of the Office on Hong Kong and Macao Affairs
under the State Council yesterday introduced China's policies on
the nationality and right of residency of the Hong Kong residents
after July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the matter will be handled in strict
accordance with the provisions of the Basic law.
</P>
<P>
"Beijing Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- A food hygiene inspecting team sent by the Standing
Committee of the National People's Congress has completed its
inspection tour in China's capital Beijing. The team was reported
to be satisfied with Beijing in this respect.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- After decades of efforts, Chinese agronomists have
successfully turned 50 million mu (about 3.3 million hectares) of
alkaline land into fertile farmland in the Huanghuaihai Plain in
central China, one of China's major grain-producing areas.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- China plans to launch two domestically made satellites
aboard its Long March 3 rockets in the next few months, the paper
reported.
</P>
<P>
"The Dongfanghong-3 (East is Red) telecommunications satellite
will be launched aboard a Long March 3A rocket in early May", the
paper says.
</P>
<P>
-- China's Ministry of Forestry plans to expand the range of
co-operative projects with the World Wildlife Fund for Nature in
the field of nature conservation.
</P>
<P>
Over the weekend the World Wildlife Fund for Nature opened its
China Programme Office in Beijing. 
</P>
