<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing's Non-Government-Run Technology Enterprises Boosted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Non-government-run technology
enterprises in Beijing have gained in both numbers and economic
scales, after ten years of development.
</P>
<P>
Started in the late 1980s in the "Zhongguancun Electronic
Street," the first high-tech industrial park in China, these
Beijing enterprises, private or institutionally-run, totaled more
than 12,000 by the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The total income of city's non-governmental technology
enterprises reached nearly 30 billion yuan (3.7 billion US
dollars) last year, 38 times the figure when they first got
started ten years ago.
</P>
<P>
Their industrial output reached more than 15 billion yuan (1.8
billion US dollars) in 1996, accounting for 10 percent of the
city's total and 100 times more than that of 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
More than 1 billion yuan (125 million US dollars) of taxes were
paid by these technology enterprises last year, which was 25
times more than that of 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
After ten years of development, a number of these enterprises
have grown into internationally competitive ones. The
Beida-Founders, a computer group company run by Beijing
University, for example, has dominated the international market in
computer-aided Chinese character composition and printing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
