<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Every Township Gets A Hospital In Northwest China's Xinjiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Farmers and herdsmans in northwest
China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region no longer need to walk
hundreds of kilometers to see a doctor as they used to do.
</P>
<P>
All 846 townships in the region have established at least one
hospital of their own. In many villages the farmers or herdsmans
even have their own commune hospitals or clinics.
</P>
<P>
Becauses of historical and geographic reasons, rural medical
and health services have long remained a weakness in Xinjiang.
</P>
<P>
Even by the year 1991, more than ten percent of the Region's
townships had not established their own hospitals. Townships that
had their own hospitals were handicapped by lack of funds, poor
equipment, and backward technologies.
</P>
<P>
In 1991, a decision was made to improve the medical and health
service by the government of the autonomous region.
</P>
<P>
To date, 140 million yuan (17 million US dollars) of special
purpose funds have been allocated by the central government and
the government of the autonomous region to promote the rural
medical sector in Xinjiang.
</P>
<P>
During the past several years, 104 township hospitals have been
built, and 619 have been upgraded or expanded, in addition to the
autonomous region's efforts to improve the rural medical equipment
and train professionals.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey conducted by the public health department
of the region, last year the number of rural patients that visited
doctors went up by 16.4 percent, and the number of patients
hospitalized up 24.8 percent in the autonomous region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
