<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Long March Launch Readied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 14 (Xinhua) -- China plans to launch two
domestically made satellites aboard its Long March 3 rockets in
the next few months, according to a senior official with the China
Aerospace Corp (CASC).
</P>
<P>
The Dongfanghong-3 (East is Red) telecommunications satellite
will be launched aboard a Long March 3A rocket in early May, said
Vice-President Xia Guohong of CASC.
</P>
<P>
It is the first satellite that China Great Wall Industries Corp
(CGWIC), a CASC affiliate, will launch this year after two
failures.
</P>
<P>
The Fengyun-2 meteorological satellite will be put into orbit
by a Long March 3 rocket in early July, Xia said. Both rockets
would be launched from China's Xichang Satellite Launch Center in
Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
Effective preparation is under way for the planned launches,
Xia said.
</P>
<P>
After the two launches, Mabuhay, a Philippine
telecommunications satellite, is also scheduled, Xia said.
</P>
<P>
With a capability to lift as much as a 5-metric-ton payload
into Geostationary Transfer Orbit, the powerful LM 3B was
developed on the basis of Long March 3A. In its first launch in
February of last year, however, the rocket failed to send an
Intelsat communications satellite into space.
</P>
<P>
After Mabuhay, the LM 3B will have two more space missions to
launch the Apstar IIR of Hong Kong and ChinaSat-1, which were
originally scheduled in early 1997 and in September of 1997
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The Apstar IIR will replace the Apstar II that was destroyed in
a failed launch in January of 1995.
</P>
<P>
Last year, after signing the agreement with China Carrier
Rocket Technology Research Institute, the LM 3B manufacturer,
China Oriental Telecom Satellite Company Ltd (COTSCL), owner of
the ChinaSat-1, said the company was confident of the basic
reliabilities of the LM-3 launch vehicle series.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
