<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (21-22) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Following are the ABCs of the
Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (21-22)
in a question-and-answer format:
</P>
<P>
Question: Will private real estate and properties of Hong Kong
people be nationalized after 1997?
</P>
<P>
Answer: Since capitalism will continue in Hong Kong after 1997
and since the protection of private property is the nucleus of the
capitalist system, the Basic Law has given great priority to
protecting the right of private property ownership for Hong Kong
residents.
</P>
<P>
Article 6 of the Basic Law explicitly stipulates, "The Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region shall protect the right of
private ownership of property in accordance with law."
</P>
<P>
Article 105 of the law again makes this provision: "The Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region shall, in accordance with law,
protect the right of individuals and legal persons to the
acquisition, use, disposal and inheritance of property and their
right to compensation for lawful deprivation of their property.
</P>
<P>
Such compensation shall correspond to the real value of the
property concerned at the time and shall be freely convertible and
paid without undue delay."
</P>
<P>
So private real estate and properties of Hong Kong residents
will not be nationalized after 1997.
</P>
<P>
Question: Will Hong Kong residents have freedom of speech and
other freedoms?
</P>
<P>
Answer: Freedom of speech, publication, assembly, association,
procession and demonstration is a right for residents to conduct
normal social and political activities, and participate in the
administration of local affairs.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law not only provides for the various rights and
freedoms of Hong Kong residents in 16 paragraphs in Chapter Three
but also stipulates that provisions of the International Covenant
on Civil and Political Rights, the International Covenant on
Economic, Social and Cultural Rights, and international labor
conventions that are applicable in Hong Kong remain in force and
be implemented through laws of the Hong Kong SAR. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
