<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central China Province to Speed Up Highway Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Hunan Province
plans to invest 17 billion yuan into local highway and bridge
construction projects in the 1996-2000 period, expecting to extend
the provincial highways to 61,600 kilometers by the turn of the
century.
</P>
<P>
Priority will given to provincial sections of the highway
linking Beijing and coastal Zhuhai in South China, the highway
linking Changde and the provincial capital Changsha, and 15 other
important trunk roads.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, a 1.2 billion-yuan highway linking Changsha and
Xiangtan was put to use, the first ever such high-speed
transportation line in the province.
</P>
<P>
During the 1991-1995 period, the province invested 7.4 billion
yuan in fixed assets in local transportation construction.
</P>
<P>
In 1993 the province listed some highway construction projects,
linking Changsha, Xiangtan and Laiyang, to attract more than 300
million US dollars of overseas investment from international
financial organizations.
</P>
<P>
During recent years, Hunan has raised more than one billion
yuan for developing local transportation networks, stretching the
local highways to more than 30,000 kilometers, including 800
kilometers of high-grade highway, and adding more than 600
bridges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
