<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Rebel Group Boosts Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 14 (Xinhua) -- Some 5,000 disgruntled members of
a former Philippine Muslim rebel group have joined the Moro
Islamic Liberation Front (MILF), which still opposes the
Philippine government, during the past months.
</P>
<P>
With the joining of these Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF)
members, the MILF now has a force of 14,900 men, with 9,300 arms,
today's local press reports quoted the military as saying on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The MNLF fighters left their group because they do not believe
they are bound by the September peace agreement on Mindanao, said
a ranking military official on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
The MNLF and the government concluded a peace agreement last
September, ending nearly three decades of armed conflicts in the
southern Philippines between the government forces and the MNLF,
the then largest Muslim separatist group.
</P>
<P>
The MNLF guerrillas who have already transferred to the MILF
reportedly came from the provinces of Zamboanga, Basilan and Sulu
in the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The military official said the MILF leadership, in turn, sent
"token firearms" to its new members as "a symbol of support." But
he did not say what the military would do about this latest
development.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, a splinter group of the MNLF and currently the
largest anti-government force in the country, has refused to
accept the peace deal signed between the MNLF and the government.
</P>
<P>
The MILF began its own peace talks with the government in
January, but the talks have been on-and-off because of sporadic
fighting between the MILF guerrillas and the government forces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
