<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unemployment in UK reaches 14 Percent: NSBC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Britain's unemployment is probably
more than twice as high than the official figure shows, according
to a new study.
</P>
<P>
The study, carried out by the HSBC, suggested the true rate of
unemployment in Britain is 14 percent -- or four million people, and
higher than in Germany.
</P>
<P>
The Government announced that Britain had 1.7 million jobless,
or 6.2 percent of the working population.
</P>
<P>
But the HSBC report argued that the Government had ignored
inconvenient categories such as those working part-time, young
people on training schemes and those who have gone on to sickness
or disability benefit rather than the dole.
</P>
<P>
The findings, disclosed by HSBC's chief economist Roger Bootle,
could not have come at a more embarrassing time for the
Conservatives, who plan to move the general election campaign on
to jobs this week.
</P>
<P>
The official figure puts Britain at the bottom of the European
Union jobless league, which is claimed the result of Conservative
policies: deregulating the labor market, opting out of the Social
Chapter and rejecting a minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
However, the HSBC report said that when definitions set by the
International Labor Organisation are used, and the impact of
hidden unemployment is taken into account, unemployment in Britain
could be more greater.
</P>
<P>
The HSBC pointed out that it is much harder to qualify for the
dole in Britain than in France or Germany, and students and those
under 18 are not counted.
</P>
<P>
Differences in the treatment of part-timers -- 800,000 of whom
in the Britain would like a "proper" job -- also understate the
rate, the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970414.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK's Pound Probably to Stay High Until Autumn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Although the pound has overvalued
about 18 percent since last August, it is likely to stay strong until
this autumn, according to currency strategists in the City.
</P>
<P>
They said that a fairly stronger domestic demand and the US
rate hike have revived expectations of a risk in UK rates soon
after the general election and this in turn will renew the pound's
upward momentum.
</P>
<P>
"We can carry on for a while yet with sterling," said Ian
Gunner, senior economist at Chase Manhattan in the City.
</P>
<P>
It is commonly believed that the pound is likely to continue to
benefit from its main support: high British interest rates.
</P>
<P>
With base rates at 6 percent, compared with a german rate of 3
percent and Japanese rates of 0.5 percent, foreign money has been
sucked into high yielding pound deposits.
</P>
<P>
The currency strategists said, even if Britain's rates rise
slowly, they are likely to remain well above overseas levels for
the next few months.
</P>
<P>
Rates in Germany and Japan appear to be on hold until those
economies start recovering, they added.
</P>
<P>
Both the Conservatives and the Opposition Party may want to
weaken the pound, but it would be hard for whichever party wins
the general election to do so.
</P>
<P>
But these currency experts believe that if Labor wins the
election, it is expected to tighten monetary policy almost
immediately on taking over at the Treasury.
</P>
<P>
The pound closed in London at the weekend at a
four-and-a-half-year high of DM2.802 against the D-Mark and 1.625
US dollars against the dollar. But they said that by the end of
the year the pound should have fallen to about DM2.62. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
