<HEADLINE> Athens Moves to Better Ties with Ankara, Skopje </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Greece was preparing to launch an
international initiative in order to improve the general climate
in the Balkan region, including its relations with Ankara and
Skopje, according to local reports today.
</P>
<P>
The Greek newspaper "The Tribune" reported today that Greek
Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos would call a summit meeting of
his counterparts from the countries such as Turkey, The former
Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia (FYROM), Albania, Bulgaria,
Yugoslavia, Romania and Bosnia-Herzegovina, to be held in June in
the Greek northern city of Thessaloniki.
</P>
<P>
Pangalos reportedly sent letters to his counterparts last week
briefing them on Greece's plans for such a meeting.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper also quoted the well-informed sources as saying
that Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis wanted a meeting with his
Turkish counterpart Necmettin Erbakan if talks between their
foreign ministers produced some indication of positive intent on
the part of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
It mentioned the three new elements in Athens' position.
Firstly, the fact that Greece accepts direct bilateral dialogue at
the level of a committee of experts; Secondly, that these experts'
committees would be authorized to record bilateral problems and
differences. Finally, it observed that for the first time in
decades Athens appeared ready to discuss the demilitarization of
the Dodecanese islands in the eastern Aegean on the condition that
Turkey carried out similar moves, mainly concerning its large
landing fleet and fourth army.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Greek Defense Minister Akis
Tsohatzopoulos today denied the recent press reports here that
Athens had started secret dialogue with Turkey over issues of
their common interest.
</P>
<P>
"I am not aware of any Greek-Turkish dialogue," he said.
</P>
<P>
Athens has repeated that Greek-Turkish relations can not be
improved before Ankara takes its claims to the Imia islets in the
eastern Aegean to the International Court of Justice at The Hague
and finds a peaceful solution to the Cyprus problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
