<DOCNO> XIE19970414.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1 South Lebanon Army Militia Killed by Guerrillas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 13 (Xinhua) -- One member of the Israeli-backed
South Lebanon Army (SLA) militia was killed and two others
wounded this afternoon when anti-Israeli guerrillas detonated a
roadside bomb in an Israeli-occupied border strip in south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Sources in the Israeli surrogate militia confirmed that the
bomb was detonated by remote control at 4:30 p.m. (13:30 GMT)
as a SLA military vehicle was rolling on a road near the town of
Tair Harfa in the western sector of the Israeli self-carved
"security zone."
</P>
<P>
The sources said on the condition of anonymity that one SLA
officer was killed and his two companions were wounded.
</P>
<P>
No Lebanese militant faction has claimed responsibility for
the attack, which added the casualties of the militia since this
year to three killed and 17 injured.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah, or the Iranian-backed Party of God, spearheads a
guerrilla warfare in south Lebanon to oust the Israeli forces
from the border enclave.
</P>
<P>
The Shiite fundamentalist party has apparently turned its
armed muscle at the 2,500-strong SLA militia since this month,
and carried out three major operations against them, in which two
militiamen were killed and seven wounded, but refrained from
hitting the Israeli occupation forces.
</P>
<P>
The last bloody attack on the Israelis took place on March 19
when Hezbollah militants killed one Israeli soldier and wounded
three others.
</P>
<P>
Security sources in south Lebanon said that the Israeli
occupation forces and the SLA militia this morning swept with
machine-gun fire the vicinities of their positions at Barasheet
and Haddatha.
</P>
<P>
They also opened fire at the areas around the villages of
Zibgin, Mansouri and Yater in the western part of south Lebanon,
and no casualties were reported.
</P>
<P>
Israel established the 1,100-square-kilometer "security zone"
in south Lebanon in 1985 to protect northern Israel from
cross-border attacks. Since then, clashes and frictions haunt
south Lebanon and make it the last active battlefront of the
Arab-Israeli conflict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
