<HEADLINE> Egyptian FM Meets with Somali Faction Leader Aideed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa today met with Somali faction leader Hussein Fareh Aideed
in his latest efforts to reconcile the warring factions in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Moussa told reporters that the talks, held
this evening, were important as they completed the Egyptian
consultations with various Somali faction leaders in a bid to end
the raging armed conflicts in the Horn of Africa.
</P>
<P>
"It is crucial that all Somali leaders find common ground for
ending the existing problem in the country," he added.
</P>
<P>
Aideed, leader of the most powerful militia in the southern
half of the Somali capital, Mogadishu, arrived here Friday.
</P>
<P>
His visit followed the one paid last month by his rivals in the
Somali National Salvation Council, an umbrella group representing
26 factions fighting him.
</P>
<P>
Two weeks ago, Ali Mahdi Mohamed, leader of Mogadishu's
northern section, also came here to meet Egyptian officials
mediating in the six-year Somali conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Arab League Secretariat sources said today Aideed
and his accompanying delegation will meet with the Arab Seven-Man
Committee concerned with the Somali crisis, comprising Egypt,
Tunisia, Libya, Sudan, Algeria, Djibouti and Yemen.
</P>
<P>
Arab League Secretary General Esmat Abdul-Meguid, in his
capacity as chairman of the meeting, will get acquainted with
Aideed's view regarding means to settle the crisis and realize
national detente.
</P>
<P>
The Arab League will intensify its efforts in the near future
along with many Arab countries and international organizations to
bring closer disputing Somali factions, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1991 ouster of the late President Mohamed Siad Barre,
Somalia has been fragmented into fiefdoms protected by factional
leaders, who continued to fight to expand their turfs despite
several peace conferences.
</P>
<P>
The factional fighting, combined with a 1992 famine, has
claimed about 350,000 lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
