<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food Prices on Rise in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Prices of basic food items have
risen by about 40 to 70 percent across Nigeria since the
beginning of this year, making life difficult for many families,
especially those with fixed income.
</P>
<P>
This was the result of recent investigations conducted in parts
of the country by the official New Nigerian newspaper.
</P>
<P>
In Nigeria's commercial center of Lagos, a bag of rice now
sold for over 40 U.S. Dollars as against 30 U.S. Dollars in
January. Prices of beans and yam tubers also continued to rise.
</P>
<P>
In the northern industrial center of Kaduna, a 100-kg bag of
maize which sold for 15 U.S. Dollars in January now costs 25 U.S.
Dollars, while the same measure of millet was priced at 30 U.S.
Dollars as against 25 U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
In capital Abuja, the price of rice and beans are also on the
rise.
</P>
<P>
The price rise was believed to be related to the current fuel
crisis in the Africa's largest oil-producing country, though many
experts said the seasonal increase in food prices was normal.
</P>
<P>
However, according to the National Committee of Heads of
Agricultural Colleges, the 1997 food problem is bound to be worse
in view of the decline in farm harvests recorded in the last
cropping season.
</P>
<P>
Leonard Agbo, chairman of the committee, disclosed that the
nation's food output declined by 21 percent in 1996 over the
previous season.
</P>
<P>
While disagreement exits among experts on the cause of decline
in food production last year, many said the shortage of
fertilizer in the year is largely responsible for the shortfall.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, investigators were also surprised to find that the
cost of manufactured goods such as milk and sugar still remained
relatively stable despite the price hike of basic food items.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
