<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Likely to Ban Non-Oil Imports from </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The British government may
prohibit the import from Nigeria of non-oil products, mainly
perishable items such as vegetables and fruits, citing its
substandard quality.
</P>
<P>
According to a confidential report sent here today by the
Nigerian High Commission in London, the possible ban would put 36
billion Naira (about 424 million U.S. Dollars) of Nigeria's
annual export revenue at risk.
</P>
<P>
Britain has remained Nigeria's leading trading partner in
non-oil products, accounting for more than one-third of such
exports from Nigeria annually.
</P>
<P>
An official of the British Customs and Excise Department,
Jeffrey Herbert, was quoted by the report as saying that most
Nigerian goods imported into Britain, especially agricultural
products, had substandard quality and were often infested with
insects and rodents.
</P>
<P>
Such products were usually destroyed on arrival, causing
serious losses to importers as well as to Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
If the problem is not checked, it could lead to a ban by the
British government on the importation of some goods from Nigeria.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
