<HEADLINE> Kenyan Air Controllers in Mass Exodus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's aviation sector lost 30
percent of air traffic controllers by 1995 and the situation is
still worsening, the local newspaper Sunday Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of Kenya Air Traffic Controllers Association, Erastus
Njogu, was quoted by the paper as saying on Saturday that more
controllers were leaving the Kenyan Air Traffic Department in
search of greener pastures.
</P>
<P>
At the association's annual meeting held here, Stanley Murage,
Permanent Secretary in the Ministry of Transport and
Communications, acknowledged the mass exodus, adding that the
Kenyan government would address the salary problem of aviation
staff.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan air traffic controllers downed their tools last year
for several days demanding better pay which the government had
promised to review and implement.
</P>
<P>
However, Njogu said that the salary hike has not yet been
implemented in the air traffic department.
</P>
<P>
The average monthly salary of Kenyan air controllers is about
100 U.S. Dollars, far below the 2000-U.S.-Dollar salary provided
by other airliners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
