<HEADLINE> Mozambique to Open Airline Between Beira, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique Airlines (LAM) is to
formally open a weekly-scheduled flight between Beira, central
Mozambique, and Johannesburg, South Africa's biggest commercial
center, the local Domingo newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
An opening ceremony will be held on Monday, first in
Johannesburg, then in Beira, the report quoted Aderito Macaba,
LAM's Commercial Director, as saying in Beira on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
About 80 delegates from the two countries, including a deputy
minister in Mozambique's Ministry of Transport and
Telecommunications, will attend the ceremony, he said.
</P>
<P>
A Fokker-100 plane, leased from Swaziland last year, will be
used in the Beira-Johannesburg maiden flight, said Macaba.
</P>
<P>
The move will improve air service in central and southern
Mozambique, he said.
</P>
<P>
Currently, people living there have to travel to capital
Maputo first for flying to South Africa, he said.
</P>
<P>
The new flight is expected to be profitable since quite a lot
of tourists and businessmen from South Africa now intend to visit
central and northern Mozambique and many Mozambicans there also
frequently travel to South Africa, he noted.
</P>
<P>
However, Mozambicans now can get visas only in Maputo, but the
problem will be solved soon, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
