<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Govt Urged to Raise National life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Former Tanzania President
Julius Nyerere today called on the government to find ways to
raise national life expectancy from currently 52 years to at
least 70.
</P>
<P>
"Our people are still dying too young compared to the life
expectancies in developed countries. We are wasting too many
lives, especially children many of whom never live to see their
fifth birthdays," he said at his 75th birthday party here today.
</P>
<P>
"In the South, including Tanzania, reaching my age is a
privilege. The majority of the people don't reach my age, that's
a pity," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said when the country declared independence some
36 years ago, life expectancy of Tanzanians stood at only 30
years old.
</P>
<P>
Organization of African Unity Secretary-General Salim Ahmed
Salim, representatives of United States President Bill Clinton
and French President Jacque Chirac, and more than 1000 other
figures attended his birthday gathering.
</P>
<P>
He said he hopes he would see the third-generation government
finish its 10-year term under the leadership of incumbent
Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa and witness Tanzania's fourth
president to assume office in 2005.
</P>
<P>
"I don't see why I should not be able to reach 100 years if my
mother has managed. I'm very healthy and this is what the
government should strive to achieve for Tanzanians," he said.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere exhorted Tanzanians to maintain the ten-year culture
of retirement for presidents, saying it is a healthy system.
</P>
<P>
He retired from presidency 12 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, retired Tanzanian president Ali Hassan Mwinyi said he
wished Nyerere a longer life. 
</P>
</TEXT>
